From the logs, the root cause is clear.

What happened

Your ImageSetConfiguration is:

mirror:
  platform:
    graph: true
    channels:
      - name: stable-4.20
        minVersion: 4.20.30
        maxVersion: 4.20.30

During mirrorToDisk, oc-mirror reports:

images to copy 1
✓ graph-image:latest -> cache

A valid OpenShift release mirror for a platform release should copy hundreds of images (typically 200–400+), not just one.

Because the tarball contains only the graph-image, when you run diskToMirror it fails with:

[GetReleaseReferenceImages] no release images found


---

Possible causes

1. Verify the release exists

Run on the connected bastion:

oc adm release info quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release:4.20.30-x86_64

If this fails with manifest unknown or not found, then 4.20.30 is not available.


---

2. Check the update graph

Run:

oc adm upgrade

or

oc adm release info --commits quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release:4.20.30-x86_64


---

3. Try disabling graph mirroring

Edit the YAML:

apiVersion: mirror.openshift.io/v2alpha1
kind: ImageSetConfiguration

archiveSize: 4

mirror:
  platform:
    channels:
      - name: stable-4.20
        minVersion: 4.20.30
        maxVersion: 4.20.30

Remove:

graph: true

Then rerun:

oc-mirror -c imageset-config_4_20_30.yaml file:///root/kamal --v2

If it still copies only one image, the issue is not the graph option.


---

4. Check your oc-mirror version

Run:

oc-mirror version

and

oc version


---

Most likely issue

Based on the logs, oc-mirror is not finding the 4.20.30 release payload, so it mirrors only the update graph image. That is why the disconnected import reports "no release images found."

To confirm exactly why, please provide the output of these commands from the connected bastion:

oc-mirror version

oc version

oc adm release info quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-release:4.20.30-x86_64

tar -tf mirror_000001.tar | head -20

Those four outputs will confirm whether the problem is:

the release doesn't exist,

an oc-mirror bug,

or a configuration issue.
